I'm going to suggest deleting. [[User:Syzergy|Syzergy]] 03:47, 23 May 2006 (UTC) :Well, I began by not being freaked out. It desperately needs wikifying, but Eileen Nearn is a link from [[Special Operations Executive]], so the article should be created at some point. I've added a little bit from some brief research, to make the context clearer. Of course, if it does turn out to be copy-vio, it will need to be re-done from scratch. [[User:JackyR|JackyR]] | [[User talk:JackyR|Talk]] 03:21, 24 May 2006 (UTC) ==Death== I cannot believe she and her siblings were not awarded the [[Order of the Bath]] or the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] for their efforts. Outrageous. [[User:Rms125a@hotmail.com|Rms125a@hotmail.com]] ([[User talk:Rms125a@hotmail.com|talk]]) 03:52, 14 September 2010 (UTC) :: Also, : More to the point re her death. It should be noted that she did not die on 2 September 2010; that was the date her body was found. Also until her date of birth are known, 1921 can only be a best guesstimate as her year of birth. [[User:Rms125a@hotmail.com|Rms125a@hotmail.com]] ([[User talk:Rms125a@hotmail.com|talk]]) 05:04, 14 September 2010 (UTC) == [[MBE]] or [[OBE]]? == There seems to be contradictory reporting on this point. MBE: [http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/sep/21/spy-eileen-nearne-heroine-burial Guardian] OBE: [http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2010/10/28/world/europe/AP-EU-Britain-Wartime-Heroine.html?hp New York Times (via Associated Press)] Since the majority of reports (and so far, all UK reports) say MBE, I think we should stick with that for now. It is possible (indeed, likely) that the AP reporter may not have firm knowledge of the distinction. I thought I would flag this here in case future reporting sheds more detailed light on the matter.--[[User:Jimbo Wales|Jimbo Wales]] ([[User talk:Jimbo Wales|talk]]) 23:30, 28 October 2010 (UTC) :I have added a link to the official announcement in the London Gazette for the MBE.
